<p class="body">Sumatra coffee is the outlier origin. Every other region on the specialty coffee map produces cups that vary in acidity, sweetness, and fruit character but share a recognizable brightness and clarity. Sumatra produces none of those things. What it produces instead is the heaviest body, the lowest acidity, and the most distinctive earthy-chocolate-cedar flavor profile in coffee. Experienced tasters recognize it blind. Novices are often startled by how different it tastes from what they expected coffee to be.</p>

<p class="body">The explanation is both geographic and technical. Sumatra's equatorial lowlands produce a different plant character than the high-altitude African and Latin American origins. But the decisive factor is a processing method found almost nowhere else on earth: wet-hull processing, called Giling Basah in Indonesian, which transforms the bean's chemistry in a way that washed and natural processing never does. Understanding that method is the key to understanding Sumatra.</p>

<p class="body"><a href="https://www.volcanicacoffee.com" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" style="color: var(--gold); text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 1px solid rgba(201,168,76,0.35);">Volcanica Coffee</a> carries Sumatra Mandheling within their catalog of 150+ single origins, roasted fresh from Atlanta, and represents the most accessible way for specialty buyers to explore this origin. Their Sumatra Mandheling is the reference point for this guide.</p>

<h2 class="section-head">The Wet-Hull Process: <em>Why Sumatra Tastes Different</em></h2>

<p class="body">Coffee processing refers to how the seed is separated from the cherry and dried before export. The three major methods, washed (pulped and dried clean), natural (dried whole cherry), and honey (pulped but with mucilage left during drying), all remove the outer parchment layer before the bean reaches the exporter. Wet-hull does something fundamentally different.</p>

<p class="body">In wet-hull processing, the cherry is pulped and allowed a short fermentation (12-24 hours), then partially dried to around 30-40% moisture content. At that point, the parchment is mechanically removed while the bean is still moist and pliable. The exposed bean then finishes drying in open air at a much higher moisture content than any other processing method would allow.</p>

